{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Einsatzgruppen'' reports}}
{{Infobox holocaust event
| name          = ''Einsatzgruppen'' reports
| image         = {{location mark+ |float=center |image=Karte - Einsatzgruppen in der Sowjetunion 1941.png |width=250 |marks=
  {{location mark~ |label={{small|'''Vileyka'''}} |mark=Red pog.svg |x%=24.8 |y%=42.5 |width=250 }}
  {{location mark~ |label='''{{small|EG-}}A''' |mark=Blanksvg.svg |x%=1.2 |y%=45.8 |width=250 }}
  {{location mark~ |label='''{{small|EG-}}B''' |mark=Blanksvg.svg |x%=0.2 |y%=58.2 |width=250 }}
  {{location mark~ |label='''{{small|EG-}}C''' |mark=Blanksvg.svg |x%=2.5 |y%=68.8 |width=250 }}
  {{location mark~ |label='''{{small|EG-}}D''' |mark=Blanksvg.svg |x%=21.8 |y%=85.8 |width=250 }}
}} {{-}} Map of the ''Einsatzgruppen'' operations with the location of the first shooting of Jewish women and children (along with the men), July 30, 1941.{{-}}
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B0716-0005-007, Oberstes Gericht, Globke-Prozess, Beweisstück.jpg|220px|border|link=Jäger Report]]<small>{{-}}The [[Jäger Report]], December 1, 1941.{{-}}</small>
| incident_type = The ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]'' shootings
| organizations = ''[[Schutzstaffel]]'' (''SS'') 
| victims       = 
}}
The '''''Einsatzgruppen'' Operational Situation Reports''' ('''OSR'''s), or '''ERM''' for the {{lang-de|Die Ereignismeldung UdSSR}} (plural: ''Ereignismeldungen''), were dispatches of the [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] death squads (''[[Einsatzgruppen]]''), which documented the progress of [[the Holocaust]] behind [[German-Soviet Frontier Treaty|the German-Soviet frontier]] in the course of [[Operation Barbarossa]], during World War&nbsp;II. The extant reports were sent between June 1941 and April 1942 to the Chief of the Security Police and the SD ({{lang-de|Chef des Sicherheitspolizei und SD}}) in Berlin, from the occupied eastern territories including modern-day Poland, Belarus, Ukraine, Russia, Moldova, and the Baltic Countries. During the [[Nuremberg War Crimes Trials]] the originals were grouped according to year and month and catalogued using a consecutive numbering system, as listed in the below table. The original photostats are held at the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives in Washington D.C.]].<ref name=heart>{{cite web |work=Einsatzgruppen Operational Situation Reports |title=Index |publisher=HolocaustResearchProject.org |author=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/einsatz/situationreport.html}}</ref><ref>[[Yitzhak Arad]], with Shmuel Krakowski and Shmuel Spector (1989), ''[http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/17296729?selectedversion=NBD6701728 The Einsatzgruppen reports: selections from the dispatches of the Nazi Death Squads’ campaign against the Jews July 1941-January 1943]'', New York, N.Y.: Holocaust Library. Edition details.</ref> 

==Background==
{{Main|Einsatzgruppen}}
Following the onset of Operation Barbarossa, during the first 5 weeks of their shooting actions, the ''[[Einsatzgruppen]]'' squads targeted primarily male Jews. This changed on July 29, 1941, when [[Reinhard Heydrich]] himself, quoted at an SS meeting in [[Vileyka]] (Polish [[Wilno Voivodeship (1926–1939)|Wilejka]]), criticized their leaders for the low execution figures. It was therefore ordered that the Jewish women and children be included in all subsequent shooting operations. The first women and children were killed along with the men on July 30, 1941, in Vileyka.<ref name="Kay">{{cite book |title=The Making of an SS Killer |first=Alex J. |last=Kay |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2016 |pages=57, 72 |ISBN=1107146348 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=r0jGCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA57}}</ref>

The Nazi ''Einsatzgruppen'' were not the only formation tasked with the mass killings. Other formations included the [[Ordnungspolizei#Police Battalions|Order Police battalions]] from Germany (Orpo) participating equally in the mass murder of Polish and Soviet Jews regardless of their age and sex,{{sfnp|Browning|2004|p=232}} including in the territories of the formerly [[Soviet invasion of Poland|Soviet-occupied Poland]] (see the [[Białystok Ghetto#Operation Barbarossa|Red Friday massacre]]), the Baltic states, and in the USSR proper.{{sfnp|Browning|1998|p=11|ps=: On the eve of Operation Barbarossa Major Weiss disclosed to his men the directives of Hitler's [http://www.mrclancy.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/Barbarossa-Decree.pdf 'Barbarossa Decree'.]}} Significant numbers of women and children were murdered behind all front lines not only by the Germans but also by the local [[Ukrainian Auxiliary Police|Ukrainian]] and [[Lithuanian Auxiliary Police Battalions|Lithuanian auxiliary forces]].{{sfnp|Browning|2004|p=261}} The largest [[mass shooting]] of Soviet Jews took place on September 29, 1941, in the ravine of [[Babi Yar]] near Kiev, where 33,771 Jews of all ages were machine-gunned (Situation Report No. 101).{{sfnp|Laqueur|Baumel|2001|p=51}}

==Original German cables==
After World War II, the reports were grouped and numbered by the Allies in order to summarize their content. The actual German cables were sent in their own differing sequence including by the ''Einsatzgruppe'' A (EG–A) attached to [[Army Group North]], ''Einsatzgruppe'' B (EG–B) attached to [[Army Group Center]], ''Einsatzgruppe'' C (EG-C) attached to the [[Army Group South]], and ''Einsatzgruppe'' D (EG–D) attached to the [[11th Army (Wehrmacht)|11th Army]].{{r|Arad-126}} In the OSRs, individual ''Ereignismeldungen UdSSR'' (morning reports) [[abbr.]] EM, from EG–A appear in 103 different places. The reports from EG–B appear in 64 OCRs (as arranged by the Allies). The EG-C reports are listed in 77 different OCRs, and the reports from EG–D (with the least representation at source) are featured in 63 OCRs. Occasionally, large gaps appear between individual reports, caused by the lack of time or other complications including broken telephone lines in the East.{{r|tables}} Notably, in Operational Situation Report number 19, Einsatzgruppe C was changed to Einsatzgruppe B and vice versa, thus confusing further reports of their shooting actions.<ref name="Arad-126">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=DqAb5tY4Ai8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22Einsatzgruppe%20A%22%20Gumbinnen&f=false | title=The Holocaust in the Soviet Union | publisher=[[University of Nebraska Press]] | work=Google Book | date=2009 | accessdate=25 March 2015 | author=Yitzhak Arad | pages=126 | ISBN=080322270X}}</ref> 

The OSRs are far from being equal. Some of them, such as OSR 156, include translated cables from several cities and weeks of shooting actions not yet concluded with tens of thousands of victims mentioned;<ref name="EG156">{{cite web |title=Einsatzgruppen Operational Situation Reports #156 |publisher=HolocaustResearchProject.org |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/einsatz/situationreport156.html |author=H.E.A.R.T  |year=2008 |translator=Hermann Feuer}}</ref> while other Operational Situation Reports, such as OSR 67, resemble long essays describing mere investigations into partisan activities in rural countryside resulting in dozens of executions.<ref name="EG67">{{cite web |title=Einsatzgruppen Operational Situation Reports #67 |publisher=HolocaustResearchProject.org |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/einsatz/situationreport67.html |author=H.E.A.R.T  |year=2008 |translator=Hermann Feuer}}</ref> Notably, the reports do not include all killings before the end of 1942.<ref name="tables">{{cite book |title=Messages of Murder: A Study of the Reports of the Einsatzgruppen of the Security Police and the Security Service, 1941-1943 |author=Ronald Headland |publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press |year=1992 |pages=27, 92, 98-101, 146 |ISBN=0838634184 |work=Tables of Killing Statistics: ''Einsatzgruppe'' A, B, C, and D. |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Mue8a5Rwyi0C&q=%22Tables%2Bof%2BKilling%2BStatistics%22}}</ref>

The following selection of reports are available in English translation. <ref>https://www.amazon.com/Einsatzgruppen-Reports-Selections-Dispatches-1941-January/dp/0896040577</ref>  The complete set of reports is available in German.  <ref>https://www.wbg-wissenverbindet.de/4127/die-ereignismeldungen-udssr-1941</ref> <ref>https://d-nb.info/1011163101/04</ref>

