{{italic title}} [[File:General McPherson 1880.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The ''General McPherson'' in 1880]] The '''''General McPherson''''' was a ship used by the U.S. military to travel between military installations in the [[San Francisco Bay]] area. Named after Union General [[James Birdseye McPherson]], a prominent figure in the [[American Civil War]], the 109 ton two-masted Quartermaster steamer was docked at Pier 7, [[Pacific Street Wharf]], San Francisco.<ref name="Jr2011">{{cite book|last=Jr|first=Jerry Lewis Champion|title=The Fading Voices of Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxH3-mB5rCcC&pg=PA30|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=27 January 2011|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4567-1488-8|page=30}}</ref> It was a small boat, reportedly "not much larger than a tug".<ref name="Soennichsen2001"/>
The ship was the main mode of transport to [[Alcatraz Island]] during its function as a [[Alcatraz Citadel|military defense and war camp]] after the ship was built in 1867. In addition to people is also carried military supplies and water.<ref name="FanningWong2007"/> A time schedule dated 1885 shows that it traveled between San Francisco, [[Fort Mason]], the [[Presidio]], [[Alcatraz Island]] and [[Angel Island (California)|Angel Island]] twice a day and took 20 minutes to travel between [[Camp Reynolds]] and [[Washington Street Wharf]].<ref name="FanningWong2007">{{cite book|last1=Fanning|first1=Branwell|last2=Wong|first2=William|title=Angel Island|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GJW2150AQzYC&pg=PA28|accessdate=5 September 2012|date=4 April 2007|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-4719-0|page=28}}</ref>
On February 2, 1869, the vessel was badly damaged following an accidental collision with the British ship ''[[Duke of Edinburgh (ship)|Duke of Edinburgh]]''. It was repaired and continued activities until 1886 when it was replaced by the ''[[General McDowell (ship)|General McDowell]]'' and subsequently sold by the military in 1887.<ref name="Soennichsen2001">{{cite book|last=Soennichsen|first=John|title=Miwoks to Missiles: A History of Angel Island|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W9QxUW6RJlIC&pg=PA62|accessdate=5 September 2012|year=2001|publisher=Angel Island Association|isbn=978-0-9667352-2-2|page=62}}</ref><ref name="Jr2011"/>
